The farm is officially in what I like to call the awkward “teenage” stage of the growing season. Spring blooms have faded and the summer flowers are just starting to find their rhythm. While I patiently wait for lisianthus and dahlias to start blooming, I’m really enjoying the floaty + dancy bits and bobs I’m finding in the field. This phase of the growing season is a good reminder that not everything can be full blast 100% of the time. There is a necessity for slow, a necessity for calm. So I’ll also just take a second to enjoy that too 🫶🏼
•
#slowliving #chill #flowers #flowerfarm

I used to get so focused on having the perfect flower recipe. So many focal flowers, so much filler, the perfect greenery. But there would be times through the growing season where I would have lots of focal flowers and no filler, or vice versa and I felt like I couldn’t make a solid arrangement. 

So instead of focusing on the recipe, I focused on the colour palette. I love using colour blocking in my arrangements, I think it creates such a beautiful piece that lets your eyes focus on certain spots and then dance around to another. This arrangement is made up of mostly filler flowers, and it still looks cool because the colours are BOMB 💣 so don’t get too caught up in what’s blooming, instead see what cool colour combos you can come up with! I think you’ll be pleasantly surprised 🧡

#colour #colourblocking #floraldesign #flowers #flowerfarm #flowershop #creative #flowerinspo

I must admit, I have a love hate relationship with dahlias. Of course they are an incredible focal flower to grow, but man they take a lot of work. 

Aside from the whole digging and dividing process, I also bag majority of the flowers with organza bags during the growing season to protect each flower from the bugs. It takes so much effort to produce quality blooms for market! 

In seasons past I was obsessed with collecting all the varieties possible. However this year I’m getting pretty cut throat about what varieties will make it for next growing season. A few things I consider are, pest tolerance, length of stems, and production. I also look back and see what I actually used in my design work. If the quality is iffy and I didn’t use that variety in my bouquets it’s see ya later ✌🏼 

Do you have any varieties you’re kicking to the curb? 

#dahlia #flowerfarm #flowers

I’m no expert, but I did grow some bomb lisianthus this past season! Here’s how I did it 🌱

1. Started with some high quality seed from @johnnys_seeds. I grew the voyage series this season and absolutely loved the ruffled petals and soft colours. 

2. Seeded into soil blocks (used the small 20 blocker) using @promixgardening all purpose mix. In the past I would make my own soil blend for my soil blocking but I kept things super simple this year and had really good germination with the all purpose promix. 

3. Once the seedlings were getting big for the blocks I potted them up into a 72 cell tray pack (again using the all purpose promix). Little tip: make sure your indoor growing room isn’t too cool and has good airflow. I had our room about 20 C and this gave me good germination and the seedlings grew at a decent pace. 

4. Hardened off and transplanted into our unheated hoop about 2 weeks before our last frost. I used frost cloth during the cooler nights for added protection.

5. Water, love and patience… and BOOM the most gorgeous lisi you could ever dream of! This is just one stem of lisianthus and our plants continued to produce more side stems all the way until fall. 
 

#gardentips #flowerfarm #garden #lisianthus #growsomethingbeautiful #flowers #florist #flowerfarmer

The foxglove really stole the show for me this season

This variety is called pink gin and is a biannual variety. The seedlings were planted in spring 2022 and didn’t bloom until spring 2023. Definitely worth the wait for the soft colours, tall stems and unique shape. 

The plants were pretty easy to tend to for the season, and they self seeded everywhere! I’m curious to see what the rows look like next season. If there will be a lot of winter damage, or just more little self seeded plants to fill in the gaps?

Let’s grow some ranunculus together! 

When I first started growing ranunculus I was very intimidated by the list of instructions that accompanied my first shipment of corms. But after growing these magnificent beauties for few years, I have found it’s not as tricky as it may sound. Here’s some little tips I’ve learned along the way: 

1. Don’t skip the pre-sprout! Soak the dried corms in room temp water for 3-4 hours. During this time the corms will plump up nice and big! 

2. Once you’ve soaked your corms place them with the octopus tentacles facing DOWN into a tray of damp potting soil and cover. Do not make the soil too wet or your corms will rot! Trust me, I’ve ruined a whole batch of corms with soggy soil 😭

3. Place the trays into a cool dark room for about 2 weeks (room temp shouldn’t be over 10 degrees— ranunculus need cool temps to root). 

4. After this time, little root should appear! You can now either plant these right into the ground, or toss under some grow lights. If you put under lights, the plants will begin to get nice and leafy. This will help the plants get a little head start when you plant into the field (especially if the temps are still on the chilly side). 

5. Ranunculus don’t like hot temps, so we usually aim to plant our spring ranunculus around March. This gives us blooms starting mid May/beginning of June.
